## Analysis of the Bug

The buggy function checks if a container type has custom handlers:

```java
private boolean _hasCustomHandlers(JavaType t) {
    if (t.isContainerType()) {
        // First: value types may have both value and type handlers
        JavaType ct = t.getContentType();
        if (ct != null) {
            return (ct.getValueHandler() != null) || (ct.getTypeHandler() != null);
        // Second: map(-like) types may have value handler for key (but not type; keys are untyped)
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

The bug is that when `ct == null`, the function falls through without checking for key handlers in map types. For maps, we should also check `t.getKeyType()` for handlers when content type is null or when dealing with map types.

## Fixed Implementation

```java
private boolean _hasCustomHandlers(JavaType t) {
    if (t.isContainerType()) {
        // First: value types may have both value and type handlers
        JavaType ct = t.getContentType();
        if (ct != null) {
            if ((ct.getValueHandler() != null) || (ct.getTypeHandler() != null)) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        // Second: map(-like) types may have value handler for key (but not type; keys are untyped)
        JavaType kt = t.getKeyType();
        if (kt != null) {
            if (kt.getValueHandler() != null) {
                return true;
            }
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

